  "20-18": (
    caption: [Activation of chloroplast fructose 1,6-bisphosphatase. Reduced fructose 1,6-bisphosphatase (FBPase-1) is activated by light and by the combination of high pH and high \[Mg21\] in the stroma, both of which are results of illumination. \[Mg21\] favors formation of the enzyme’s active Mg21 complex. Fructose 1,6-bisphosphatase requires Mg21 and is very dependent on pH (Fig. 20–18); its activity increases more than 100-fold when pH and \[Mg21\] rise during chloroplast illumination.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "20-19": (
    caption: [Light activation of several enzymes of the Calvin cycle. The light activation is mediated by thioredoxin, a small, disulfide-containing protein. In the light, thioredoxin is reduced by electrons moving from photosystem I through ferredoxin (Fd) (blue arrows), then thioredoxin reduces critical disulfide bonds in each of the enzymes sedoheptulose 1,7-bisphosphatase, fructose 1,6-bisphosphatase, ribulose 5-phosphate kinase, and glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate dehydrogenase, activating these enzymes. In the dark, the —SH groups undergo reoxidation to disulfides, inactivating the enzymes. c20CarbohydrateBiosynthesisInPlantsAndBacteria.indd Page 812 01/10/12 11:29 AM user-F408 c20CarbohydrateBiosynthesisInPlantsAndBacteria.indd Page 812 01/10/12 11:29 AM user-F408 /Users/user-F408/Desktop /Users/user-F408/Desktop 812],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
